future, Dean says in opening bidding</h2><p class="sc-gzOgki ixpUvU">From CNN's Rob Picheta</p></header><div class="sc-bdVaJa post-content-rendered render-stellar-contentstyles__Content-sc-9v7nwy-0 erzhuK"><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The Dean of Windsor is opening Queen Elizabeth II's committal service with a bidding.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"><em>"We have come together to commit into the hands of God the soul of his servant Queen Elizabeth. Here, in St, Georges Chapel, where she so often worshipped, we are bound to call to mind someone whose uncomplicated yet profound Christian faith bore so much fruit,"</em> he said.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"><em>"Fruit, in a life of unstinting service to the Nation, the Commonwealth and the wider world, but also (and especially to be remembered in this place) in kindness, concern and reassuring care for her family and friends and neighbours. </em></p><div class="sc-bdVaJa sc-RefOD bkVmOx"><blockquote class="sc-dnqmqq hJIoKL"><em>"In the midst of our rapidly changing and frequently troubled world, her calm and dignified presence has given us confidence to face the future, as she did, with courage and with hope.</em></blockquote></div><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"><em>"As, with grateful hearts, we reflect on these and all the many other ways in which her long life has been a blessing to us, we pray that God will give us grace to honor her memory by following her example, and that, with our sister Elizabeth, at the last, we shall know the joys of life eternal."</em></p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Before the Dean began his bidding, the choir sang the Russian Contakion of the Departed, which is id="h_160acec3395bc11685f41dfa58491dfe"><header class="sc-gxMtzJ ewPNtv"><span class="timeAlert sc-iujRgT llASnG">21 min ago</span><h2 class="sc-dfVpRl kvaBeP">The Queen&#x27;s committal service is taking place in the chapel that hosted her husband&#x27;s funeral and Prince Harry&#x27;s wedding</h2><p class="sc-gzOgki ixpUvU">From CNNs Max Foster and Lauren Said-Moorhouse</p></header><div class="sc-bdVaJa post-content-rendered render-stellar-contentstyles__Content-sc-9v7nwy-0 erzhuK"><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The committal service for Queen Elizabeth II will take place at St. Georges Chapel, within the walls of Windsor Castle.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Construction of the chapel begun under King Edward IV in 1475 and was completed just over 50 years later by King Henry VIII. </p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The chapel is a Royal Peculiar -- meaning a church under the direct jurisdiction of the monarch. The chapel is governed by the Dean and Canons of Windsor who -- along with their officers and staff -- are independent of the royal household. </p><div class="sc-bdVaJa sc-RefOD bkVmOx"><blockquote class="sc-dnqmqq hJIoKL">It has been the location of many royal weddings, including the Earl and Countess of Wessex in June 1999, the Duke and Duchess of Sussex in May 2018 and Princess Eugenie and Jack Brooksbank in October 2018. </blockquote></div><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Back in 2005, it was also where a service of dedication and prayer took place following the marriage of King Charles and Camilla, the Queen Consort.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Funerals have also taken place there including those of Princess Margaret and Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester. The funeral service for the Duke of Edinburgh was held at the chapel last April.</p></div><div data-open="false" class="sc-bdVaJa sc-iyvyFf hoANdN"><div class="sc-gzVnrw htmtru"><button aria-label="Open social share" data-open="false" class="sc-kPVwWT eUMOKF"><svg class="sc-kfGgVZ oXshK close-icon" style="outline:0" width="64" height="64" viewBox="0 0 64 64" fill="" class="sc-esjQYD jlSmOG share-os-icon" style="outline:0" width="64" height="64" viewBox="0 0 64 64" fill="" xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M50,34.00005 C50,32.89605 id="h_052536f655103cd6fc6a0f2fea6ff674"><header class="sc-gxMtzJ ewPNtv"><span class="timeAlert sc-iujRgT llASnG">1 hr 13 min ago</span><h2 class="sc-dfVpRl kvaBeP">Kate, Meghan and Princess Charlotte pay tribute to Queen with jewelry choices</h2><p class="sc-gzOgki ixpUvU">From CNN's Max Foster in Windsor and Lauren Kent</p></header><div class="sc-bdVaJa post-content-rendered render-stellar-contentstyles__Content-sc-9v7nwy-0 erzhuK"><div class="Box-sc-1fet97o-0 image-with-captionstyles__ImageWithCaptionWrapper-sc-17jmou0-0 eWDxVG"><figure><img src="https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/digital-images/org/41bf0097-2135-41fb-957f-cccb242c3037.jpg" alt="(Alberto Pezzali/AP)" class="Image-p11edh-0 gubAgz"/><figcaption> (Alberto Pezzali/AP)</figcaption></figure></div><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Catherine, the Princess of Wales, Meghan, the Duchess of Sussex, and Princess Charlotte, all paid tribute to Queen Elizabeth II through their symbolic jewelry choices on Monday.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The brooch that <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/19/uk/george-charlotte-queen-funeral-intl-scli-gbr/index.html" target="_blank">Princess Charlotte</a> wore to the state funeral service was a gift from her great-grandmother, Kensington Palace told CNN. The diamond brooch was small and horseshoe-shaped.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Her mother, Catherine, the Princess of Wales, also honored the late Queen through herpearl necklace and earrings, which is the same set she wore to the Duke of Edinburgh's funeral.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"></p><div class="Box-sc-1fet97o-0 image-with-captionstyles__ImageWithCaptionWrapper-sc-17jmou0-0 eWDxVG"><figure><img src="https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/digital-images/org/bd2bd266-b8dd-4176-beab-cb3e1c4cf5cc.jpg" alt="(Phil Harris/WPA Pool/Getty Images)" class="Image-p11edh-0 gubAgz"/><figcaption> (Phil Harris/WPA Pool/Getty Images)</figcaption></figure></div><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"></p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The jewelryset once belonged to the Queen, who is believed to have loaned the necklace and earrings to Kate for the first time in 2017. The Princess of Wales was pictured wearing the necklace to the Queen's70th wedding anniversary dinner.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The Japanese choker necklace has four rows of pearls and a curved central diamond clasp. Meanwhile, the drop pearl earrings are from Bahrain. Pearls are traditionally worn as mourning jewelry  partly due to their colorless, unflashy appearance  in a tradition that was cemented during the reign of Queen Victoria.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Princess Diana also previously wore the set during a state visit from Queen Beatrix of the Netherlands in 1982, and the Queen herself was pictured wearing the necklace and earrings in Bangladesh in 1983, according to the Palace.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Meghan, the Duchess of Sussex, wore understated pearl stud earrings that were also a gift from the Queen, according to a spokesperson for the Sussexes.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"></p><div class="Box-sc-1fet97o-0 image-with-captionstyles__ImageWithCaptionWrapper-sc-17jmou0-0 eWDxVG"><figure><img src="https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/digital-images/org/3e678e26-973d-4e40-bbf6-995523e7e5c7.jpg" alt="(Alberto Pezzali/AP)" class="Image-p11edh-0 gubAgz"/><figcaption> (Alberto Pezzali/AP)</figcaption></figure></div><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"></p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Meanwhile, Camilla, the Queen Consort, wore a gold necklace and sapphire stone and diamond stud earrings to the service. She also woreQueen Victoria's Hesse Diamond Jubilee Brooch, which is in the shape of an open heart and features two blue sapphire pendants.</p></div><div data-open="false" class="sc-bdVaJa sc-iyvyFf hoANdN"><div class="sc-gzVnrw htmtru"><button aria-label="Open social share" data-open="false" class="sc-kPVwWT eUMOKF"><svg class="sc-kfGgVZ oXshK close-icon" style="outline:0" width="64" height="64" The brooch that Princess Charlotte wore to the state funeral service was a gift from her great-grandmother, Kensington Palace told CNN. The diamond brooch was small and horseshoe-shaped. Her mother, Catherine, the Princess of Wales, also honored the late Queen through herpearl necklace and earrings, which is the same set she wore to the Duke of Edinburgh's funeral.   The jewelryset once belonged to the Queen, who is believed to have loaned the necklace and earrings to Kate for the first time in 2017. The Princess of Wales was pictured wearing the necklace to the Queen's70th wedding anniversary dinner. The Japanese choker necklace has four rows of pearls and a curved central diamond clasp. Meanwhile, the drop pearl earrings are from Bahrain. Pearls are traditionally worn as mourning jewelry  partly due to their colorless, unflashy appearance  in a tradition that was cemented during the reign of Queen Victoria. Princess Diana also previously wore the set during a state visit from Queen Beatrix of the Netherlands in 1982, and the Queen herself was pictured wearing the necklace and earrings in Bangladesh in 1983, according to the Palace. Meghan, the Duchess of Sussex, wore understated pearl stud earrings that were also a gift from the Queen, according to a spokesperson for the Sussexes.             "articleBody": "The second service of the day will be a more intimate occasion than the one in London earlier and will be conducted by the Dean of Windsor, who will deliver the Bidding.  Prayers will be said by the Rector of Sandringham, the Minister of Crathie Kirk, where the family worship when they are in residence at Balmoral, and the Chaplain of the Royal Chapel of All Saints in Windsor Great Park. The royal family will gather along with a congregation made up of members of the Royal Household, past and present, as well as personal staff who have worked on the private estates. The service will also feature several nods to the Queens family, with the choir singing The Russian Contakion of the Departed, which was also sung during Prince Philips funeral at St. Georges last April.  Meanwhile, the Dean will read Revelation 21, verses 1-7, which were read at the funerals of the Queens grandparents King George V and Queen Mary in 1936 and 1953. They were also read at the Queens fathers funeral in 1952. As the committal service draws to a close, the Queens coffin will be lowered into the Royal Vault, set beneath St. George's, as the Dean reads Psalm 103, which concludes with the words, Go forth upon thy journey from this world, O Christian soul. The Garter King of Arms will then proclaim the Queens styles and titles before her piper plays for her one last time.",

It is being sung by the Choirs of Westminster Abbey and the Chapel Royal of St. Jamess Palace. The second hymn \"The Lords my Shepherd\" was sung to the Crimond tune.The tune hails back to a parish in Aberdeenshire, not far from Balmoral Castle in Scotland where the Queen died. The hymn was also sung at the Queen's wedding to Prince Philip, and according to Buckingham Palace, the young Princess Elizabeth and Princess Margaret summoned the Master of Choristers to the Palace in the lead-up to the day, so that they could sing him the descant that would be used.             "articleBody": "Donned in a black and white feathered hat and in a hand-sewn pearl button suit, Pearly Queen Michelle Thorpe, 55, said she decided to come to the Mall -- which links Buckingham Palace to Trafalgar Square -- as she loves Queen Elizabeth II. ThePearly King and Queens are an instantly recognizable London institution dating back 150 years. They evolved from Coster Kings and Queens, who were elected as leaders of Londons street traders, according to their website. Traditionally, each Pearlie sews their own pearl button suit before being crowned, often decorated with family symbols: a heart for charity, a horseshoe for luck, for example.             "articleBody": "The State Gun Carriage carrying the Queen to Westminster Abbey has a fascinating history. In the care of the Royal Navy since 1901, it was removed from active service for Queen Victorias funeral. It has also been used for the funerals of several other monarchs, including those of King Edward VII, King George V and King George VI. It also featured in the funerals of the Queen's first prime minister, Winston Churchill, and her cousin, Lord Louis Mountbatten. In keeping with tradition, the gun carriage is being drawn by 142 Royal Naval Ratings, who are service personnel. It is flanked by the bearer party, pallbearers made up of the Queens service equerries, as well as detachments of the Kings Body Guards of the Honourable Corps of Gentlemen at Arms, The Yeomen of the Guard and the Royal Company of Archers.",

            "articleBody": "The Queens coffin is being taken in a procession from the Palace of Westminster to Westminster Abbey on the State Gun Carriage of the Royal Navy.  The coffin is draped with the Royal Standard, and the Instruments of State -- the Imperial State Crown and regalia -- are laid upon it along with a flower wreath. The wreath -- which has been made in a sustainable manner -- contains flowers and foliage cut from the gardens of Buckingham Palace, Clarence House and Highgrove House at the request of King Charles III.  It sits in a nest of English moss and oak branches. The flowers included are: scented pelargoniums; garden roses; autumnal hydrangea; sedum; dahlias; and scabious. They are all in shades of gold, pink and deep burgundy, with white elements to reflect the Royal Standard. The foliage that has been included in the wreath was selected for its symbolism -- rosemary (for remembrance), myrtle (an ancient symbol of a happy marriage), and English oak (symbolic of the strength of love). The myrtle was cut from a plant grown from a sprig of myrtle that featured in the Queens wedding bouquet when she married Prince Philip in 1947.",

            "articleBody": "As Britain mourns, Americas special relationship with its one-time colonial master completes another cycle of its enduring life. US President Joe Biden and first lady Jill Biden arrived in Britain Saturday, visiting Queen Elizabeth IIs coffin as she lay in state in the ancient Westminster Hall the following day. They later attended a reception at Buckingham Palace hosted by King Charles III and the Queen Consort. Paying tribute to the Queen earlier last week, Biden told King Charles III his mother helped strengthen their nations bonds, herdignity and constancy deepened the enduring friendship and special relationship between the United States and the United Kingdom. It is perhaps no surprise she did; her reign was born in the prime of that special relationship. It was the UKs wartime Prime Minister Winston Churchills insistent trans-Atlantic diplomacy that helped win American support for Britain in World War II. In his famous special relationship speech in Missouri on March 5,1946, sixyears before Princess Elizabeth would become Queen, Churchill suggested a creed for the nations: Here is the message of the British and American people to mankind. Let us preach what we practice --let us practice what we preach. The Queen would live Churchills words to the letter, and significantly he would be her first and formative prime minister. She would later see in another 14, although none with a reputation quite as fearsome as his. In 1946 Churchill arguably laid the groundwork for decades of close cooperation, from trying Nazi war criminals, to global peacekeeping duties, to standing alongside America after al Qaedas 9/11 attacks. The relationship worked both ways; President Bill Clinton helped the Queens government establish peace in Northern Ireland in 1998, a peace that Queen Elizabeth worked tirelessly to strengthen. During his phone call last week President Biden conveyed his wish to continue a close relationship with the King.",

            "articleBody": "London police chiefs and medics are bracing themselves for a security nightmare at theQueens funeralon Monday as they balance the need to protect the worlds top leaders and dignitaries with the desire among many to mourn their much-loved monarch. Some have compared the event in scale to the London Olympics, but in truth the state funeral  the first in Britain since Winston Churchill died in 1965  is likely to dwarf the 2012 sporting extravaganza. Codenamed Operation London Bridge, arrangements for Britains longest-serving monarch have been carefully pored over for years by the many agencies involved, with the Queen herself signing off on every detail before her death. The three police forces which operate in the British capital  the Metropolitan Police, the City of London Police and British Transport Police  initiated their well-rehearsed plans across London as soon as thedeath of Elizabeth IIwas announced on September 8. The funeral will be the largest single policing event that Londons Metropolitan Police force has undertaken, its Deputy Assistant Commissioner Stuart Cundy told reporters Friday.             "articleBody": "Monday is a Bank Holiday across the UK, with millions of people being given the chance to watch the Queen's funeral. It marks the culmination of a mourning period that has seen Britain gradually grind towards a standstill. Sporting fixtures and cultural events have been almost entirely suspended on Monday, while museums, banks, businesses, shops and schools are shut. But while those closures were mostly anticipated following the demise of a monarch whosereign lasted seven decades, others have caused more serious consequences  leaving some Brits mystified and angry. Non-urgent hospital appointments across the country have been pushed back due to staffing shortfalls, adding to an already unprecedented waiting list for health care in Britain. Holidaymakers have seen their accommodation plans torn up, travelers are warned that flights will be disrupted to avoid noise over London, and funerals and food banks are braced for disturbances. The confusion reflects a country that has wrestled with how best to honor the Queen. Despite decades of planning for Elizabeth IIs passing, the government has declined to issue firm guidance on what should and should not go ahead during the period of national mourning, leaving many decisions up to providers.             "articleBody": "The meticulously planned arrangements for the Queen's funeral are set to be a fitting farewell to Britains longest-reigning monarch. Speaking on behalf of the many agencies and departments involved in the funeral, the Earl Marshal, the Duke of Norfolk, said orchestrating the event was both humbling and daunting. He added that it aimed to unite people across the globe and resonate with people of all faiths, whilst fulfilling Her Majesty and her familys wishes to pay a fitting tribute to an extraordinary reign. Here's a rundown of what we're expecting: At around 10:35 a.m. (5:35 a.m. ET), the coffin will be lifted from the catafalque where it has been resting by a bearer party founded by the Queens Company, 1st Battalion Grenadier Guards, and carried in procession from Westminster Hall to the State Gun Carriage of the Royal Navy, a senior palace official said.\nIn keeping with tradition, the gun carriage will set off at 10:44 a.m. and begin the short journey from New Palace Yard to Westminster Abbey. The King, royal family members, and members of both households of the monarch and Prince of Wales will follow directly behind the coffin.\nThe service will be conducted by the Rev. David Hoyle, the Dean of Westminster, at Westminster Abbey, starting at 11 a.m. UK Prime Minister Liz Truss and Patricia Scotland, the Commonwealth Secretary General, will read lessons. The Archbishop of Canterbury, Justin Welby, will deliver a sermon.\nTowards the end of the service, at around 11:55 a.m., the Last Post will sound before a two-minute silence is observed. The state funeral will be brought to a conclusion by the Queens Piper, who at noon will play a Reveille, the National Anthem and a Lament. Following the state funeral, the coffin will be conveyed from the hall to Wellington Arch  again with King Charles III leading some members of the royal family behind on foot, while Camilla, the Queen Consort and others follow by car  before making its final journey out of London to Windsor. Its destination:St. Georges Chapel, within the grounds of Windsor Castle, where a committal service will take place at about4 p.m. (11 a.m. ET), conducted by the Dean of Windsor. \nA private burial service will be held for the family later, and the Queen will be laid to rest with her late husband of 73 years, Prince Philip, at the King George VI Memorial Chapel.             "articleBody": "Few people alive remember a time before Queen Elizabeth II.  Her seven-decade reign began in the aftermath of World War II; it persevered through the last throes of Britains empire, the insecurity of the Cold War and the dawn of a new millennium, providing a counterweight to the relentless pace of change. For each of those 70 years, the Queen remained the central fixture in Britains collective psyche. Her death, at the age of 96, plunged the country into mourning and an unfamiliar new age. But on Monday, the nation will say its final goodbye. Britain has ground to a halt for Elizabeth IIs state funeral, expected to be one of the most-viewed events in recent history. Crowds will line the streets of London to glimpse the procession, and leaders from countries in every part of the world have descended on the British capital. The first state funeral in Britain since Winston Churchills death in 1965, Monday marks the climax of a lengthy mourning period that has seen Britons turn out in droves to join commemorations for Elizabeth. Thousands queued for several hours to see her lying-in-state, and memorial events were held in towns, cities and villages across the country. King Charles III, Elizabeths son and heir who assumed the throne amid a wave of national mourning, will be joined by the rest of the royal family at Westminster Abbey as he pays respects to his mother later. After the service, the Queen will undertake her final journey as her coffin is driven to Windsor and the late monarch is privately buried  the end of a somber period of transition, and the last act of Britains long and momentous second Elizabethan age. The state funeral begins at 11 a.m. (6 a.m. ET). Stay with us as we take you through this historic moment for the British royal family and the nation.",

        							<div class="intro-header__bg-sm">
        								<img src="media/images/heroMobile.jpg" alt='' />
        							</div>
        							<div class="intro-header__bg-lg">
        								<img src="media/images/heroDesk.jpg" alt='' />
        							</div>
        						</div>
        						<div class="intro-header">
        							<div class="header-gradient"></div>
        							<div class="intro-header__headline">
        								<div class="headline-copy">
        									<h1>The final journey <span>London to Windsor, follow the route to the Queen's resting place</span></h1>
        								</div>
        								<div class="intro-header__sub">
        									<!-- <p class="intro-header__dek"></p> -->
        									<p class="intro-header__byline byline">By <strong>Ivana Kottasov, Lauren Said-Moorhouse and the Visuals Team, CNN</strong></p>
        								</div>
        							</div>
        						</div>
        					
        						<div class="intro-header__sub">
        							<!-- <p class="intro-header__dek"></p> -->
        							<p class="intro-header__photocredit">The Queen will be laid to rest at St. Georges Chapel, Windsor. <span>Dominic Lipinski - WPA Pool/Getty Images</span></p>
        						</div>
        					</div>
        
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							<div class="cp-text cp-story-meta container">
        								<p>Published September 18, 2022</h2>
        								<p></h2>
        							</div>
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p><span class=dropcap>A</span> kingdom united in grief will mourn the loss of their revered Queen on Monday. Pomp and pageantry will be on display as tens of thousands line the streets of the British capital and hundreds of millions tune in for the state funeral of Elizabeth II.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>Mondays ceremonial events are the culmination of nearly two weeks of public arrangements, codenamed Operation London Bridge, honoring Elizabeths remarkable life -- from a young princess who was not born to be Queen, to a sovereign who redefined the role and won almost universal admiration.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							<div class="container">
        								<div class="cp-image ivanim-fade">
        									<figure class="u-full-width">
        									  <picture class="u-full-width">
        									    <img
        									        
        									        src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=="
        									        data-src="media/images/mimg.jpg"
        									        class="lazyload u-full-width u-height-auto "
        									        alt= />
        									  </picture>
        									  <figcaption class="caption">Queen Elizabeth II lies in state at Westminster Hall early Saturday, September 17. <span class="caption__credit">Credit: Bernadette Tuazon/CNN</span></figcaption>
        									</figure>
        								</div>
        							</div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>Following the Queens death at Balmoral on September 8, her coffin was flown back from Scotland and moved to Londons Westminster Hall in a somber procession. She will lie in state there until the morning of her funeral.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>Crowds of mourners will flood the capital in the hopes of witnessing the coffin -- draped in the Royal Standard and carrying the Instruments of State -- one last time before the Queen makes the journey to her final resting place within St. Georges Chapel in Windsor. Heres everything you need to know about Britains farewell to one its greatest ever monarchs.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							<div class="gmapContainer" id="mpx_map1">
        							
        							    <div class="mapBG">
        							        <div id="map1" class="mapJs" data-zoom="16" data-display="satellite" data-lat="51.4996133" data-lng="-0.1277"></div>
        							        <div class="mobileBG">
        							            <div></div>
        							        </div>
        							    </div>
        							
        							    <div class="mapScrollyP">
        							            <div class="firstSP">
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="mp1" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.4996133" data-long="-0.1277" data-zoom="16" data-index="1">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_mp1" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Monday, September 19</strong></b><strong>The day of the funeral and the final journey to Windsor</strong></p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="abbey" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.4996133" data-long="-0.1277" data-zoom="16" data-index="2">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_abbey" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Westminster</strong> <strong>Hall</strong></b>At around 10:35 a.m. (5:35 a.m. ET), the coffin will be lifted from the catafalque. A bearer party founded by the Queen's Company, 1st Battalion Grenadier Guards will carry it from Westminster Hall to the State Gun Carriage of the Royal Navy. <br/><br/>The gun carriage will set off at 10:44 a.m. (5:44 a.m. ET) on the short journey from New Palace Yard to Westminster Abbey, where the funeral service will take place. The route will be lined by the Royal Navy and Royal Marines. King Charles III and members of the royal family will walk behind the coffin.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div class="hid">
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="abbey2" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.4996133" data-long="-0.1277" data-zoom="16" data-index="3">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_abbey2" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ></p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="abbey_service" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.4996133" data-long="-0.1277" data-zoom="" data-index="4">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_abbey_service" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Westminster</strong> <strong>Abbey</strong></b>The service will be conducted by the Dean of Westminster, starting at 11 a.m. (6 a.m. ET). The Archbishop of Canterbury, Justin Welby, will deliver a sermon. Towards the end of the service, at around 11:55 a.m., the Last Post will sound before a two-minute silence is observed.<br/><br/>World leaders, politicians, public figures and European royals, as well as more than 500 dignitaries from around the world, will be at the service, which will be attended by up to 2,000 people.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div class="streetView">
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="sv_abbey" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.501671" data-long="-0.140678" data-zoom="18" data-index="5">
        							                            <div id="sv_map1_sv_abbey" class="streetViewL">
        							                                <p class="cardText" ><b>Click below for a 360 view inside Westminster Abbey</b></p>
        							                                <div class="poster_img" style="background-image: url('media/images/sv_map1_sv_abbey.jpg');">
        							                                    <div class="view360"></div>
        							                                </div>
        							                                
        							                            </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="route1" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="6">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_route1" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Procession through London</strong></b>Following the roughly one-hour service, the coffin will be conveyed from Westminster Abbey to Wellington Arch -- again with the King leading some of the family on foot, while Camilla, the Queen Consort and others follow by car.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="whitehall" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="7">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_whitehall" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Whitehall</strong></b>The route -- lined by the Armed Forces -- will pass Parliament Square and go onto Whitehall, the street that cuts through Londons government district.<br/><br/>It will pass the Cenotaph, the site of the annual National Service of Remembrance, which the Queen personally attended most years, and Downing Street.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div class="streetView">
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="sv_whitehall" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="8">
        							                            <div id="sv_map1_sv_whitehall" class="streetViewL">
        							                                <p class="cardText" ><b>Click below for a 360 view of Whitehall by Downing Street</b></p>
        							                                <div class="poster_img" style="background-image: url('media/images/sv_map1_sv_whitehall.jpg');">
        							                                    <div class="view360"></div>
        							                                </div>
        							                                
        							                            </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="horse" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="9">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_horse" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Horse Guards Parade</strong></b>The procession moves through Horse Guards Parade, the setting for the annual Trooping the Colour ceremony held to mark the monarchs official birthday. Here, the Kings Life Guard will turn out and give a royal salute as the coffin passes.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="mall" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.504832" data-long="-0.126807" data-zoom="20" data-index="10">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_mall" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>The Mall</strong></b>On The Mall, the royal procession will pass by royal residences Clarence House and St James's Palace.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div class="streetView">
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="sv_mall" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="11">
        							                            <div id="sv_map1_sv_mall" class="streetViewL">
        							                                <p class="cardText" ><b>Click below for a 360 view of The Mall</b></p>
        							                                <div class="poster_img" style="background-image: url('media/images/sv_map1_sv_mall.jpg');">
        							                                    <div class="view360"></div>
        							                                </div>
        							                                
        							                            </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="palace" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="12">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_palace" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Buckingham Palace</strong></b>As the coffin moves past Queen Victoria Memorial for the last time, the Kings Guard will turn out in the forecourt and give a royal salute.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div class="streetView">
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="sv_palace" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.501671" data-long="-0.140678" data-zoom="18" data-index="13">
        							                            <div id="sv_map1_sv_palace" class="streetViewL">
        							                                <p class="cardText" ><b>Click below for a 360 view of The State Rooms in Buckingham Palace</b></p>
        							                                <div class="poster_img" style="background-image: url('media/images/sv_map1_sv_palace.jpg');">
        							                                    <div class="view360"></div>
        							                                </div>
        							                                
        							                            </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="arch" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="14">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_arch" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Wellington Arch</strong></b>The procession is expected at Wellington Arch around 1 p.m. (8 a.m. ET), where the bearer party will transfer it from the State Gun Carriage to the state hearse for the journey to Windsor.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="windsor" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="15">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_windsor" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Windsor</strong></b>The Queens coffin will be driven to Windsor, around 25 miles (40 kilometers) west of the capital. Windsor Castle is where the Queen lived for the last two years of her life.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="walk" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.477947" data-long="-0.6145636" data-zoom="17" data-index="16">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_walk" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>The Long Walk</strong></b>Once in Windsor, the state hearse will be driven just after 3 p.m. (10 a.m. ET) along The Long Walk, a picturesque avenue leading to the castle where thousands will be waiting to bid the Queen farewell as she passes.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="castle" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="17">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_castle" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>Windsor Castle</strong></b>The King and other royals will join the procession on foot as it passes through the castles quadrangle at around 3:40 p.m. (10:40 a.m. ET). <br/><br/>Minute guns will be fired by the Kings Troop, Royal Horse Artillery from the East Lawn throughout the royal cortege.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div class="streetView">
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="sv_castle" data-map="map1" data-lat="" data-long="" data-zoom="" data-index="18">
        							                            <div id="sv_map1_sv_castle" class="streetViewL">
        							                                <p class="cardText" ><b>Click below for a 360 view inside the grounds of Windsor Castle</b></p>
        							                                <div class="poster_img" style="background-image: url('media/images/sv_map1_sv_castle.jpg');">
        							                                    <div class="view360"></div>
        							                                </div>
        							                                
        							                            </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>
        							            <div>
        							                <div class="posC" data-id="chapel" data-map="map1" data-lat="51.4838075" data-long="-0.6088345" data-zoom="17" data-index="19">
        							                        <div id="cd_map1_chapel" class="infoCardL">
        							                            <p class="cardText" ><b><strong>St Georges Chapel</strong></b>The Queens coffin will be greeted by an honor guard founded by the 1st Battalion Grenadier Guards mounted in Horseshoe Cloister at the foot of the West Steps of St. Georges Chapel. <br/><br/>Soldiers from the Household Cavalry Mounted Regiment will line the steps as the bearer party carries the coffin inside for the committal service.</p>
        							                        </div>
        							                </div>
        							            </div>

        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>A more intimate committal service will take place at St. Georges Chapel at about 4 p.m. (11 a.m. ET), conducted by the Dean of Windsor. The royal family will gather there along with a congregation made up of members of the Royal Household, past and present, as well as personal staff who have worked on the private estates.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>St. Georges should be a familiar location to many as it is where Prince Philip's funeral service was held last April, as well as more jubilant occasions like the nuptials of the Queen's grandchildren.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>At the service's conclusion, the Queen's coffin will be lowered into the Royal Vault, set below the chapel, where many royal family members have been laid to rest.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>The service concludes the public arrangements for the late monarch, however, a private burial service will be held for the family later Monday evening. The Queen is to be buried with her late husband of 73 years, Prince Philip, in the King George VI Memorial Chapel, located elsewhere within St. George's.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>The memorial chapel is where the Queen's father and mother were interred. A casket containing the ashes of the Queen's sister, Princess Margaret, is also there.</p>
        							    </div>
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        						
        							
        							    <div class="cp-text container">
        							        <p>The Earl Marshal, the Duke of Norfolk, said last week that orchestrating the event was "both humbling and daunting. He added that Mondays event aimed to "unite people across the globe" and "pay a fitting tribute to an extraordinary reign.</p>
        							    </div>

class="sc-bdVaJa post-content-rendered render-stellar-contentstyles__Content-sc-9v7nwy-0 erzhuK"><div class="sc-dnqmqq render-stellar-contentstyles__List-sc-9v7nwy-1 eUPcFX"><ul class='cnn_rich_text'><li>The exhumation of bodies from <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/16/europe/ukraine-izium-mass-burial-site-intl-hnk/index.html" target="_blank">a mass burial site</a> id="h_f9c7e275150eefc935b8af7093afdfc5"><header class="sc-gxMtzJ ewPNtv"><span class="timeAlert sc-iujRgT llASnG">3 hr 14 min ago</span><h2 class="sc-dfVpRl kvaBeP">It&#x27;s 3 p.m. in Kyiv. Here&#x27;s what you need to know</h2><p class="sc-gzOgki ixpUvU">From CNN staff</p></header><div class="sc-bdVaJa post-content-rendered render-stellar-contentstyles__Content-sc-9v7nwy-0 erzhuK"><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Russian missile attacks across southern and northeastern Ukraine have damaged a power complex and left multiple people injured, amid an onslaught of shelling from Moscow targeting civilian infrastructure.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The Kremlin has accused the US of engaging in "media madness" after President Joe Biden personally met with the families of two American detainees last week.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"><em>Here are the latest developments:</em></p><div class="sc-dnqmqq render-stellar-contentstyles__List-sc-9v7nwy-1 eUPcFX"><ul class='cnn_rich_text'><li><strong>Moscow escalates attacks on critical facilities: </strong>Russian shelling <a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-09-19-22/h_154d1b73e6c72b2fb6b23d069cc651dd" target="_blank">injured at least two people</a>, including an 11-year-old boy, and damaged infrastructure in the northeastern region of Kharkiv over the past day, according to a local official. Further south in Mykolaiv, a Russian missile attack hit theindustrial site of the <a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-09-19-22/h_64129f028ce0c2f7f353d4e981b2f83f" target="_blank">South Ukraine Nuclear Power Plant</a>, nuclear operator Energoatom said on Monday. The attack shut down one of the hydropower units and three high-voltage power lines, but all three nuclear reactors were not damaged, Energoatom added.</li><li><strong>Zelensky says Kyiv is "preparing for liberation of more cities":</strong> Ukrainian PresidentVolodymyr<em></em>Zelenskyinsisted there is no "lull" on the frontline, saying that Kyiv's sweeping counteroffensive is rolling on in "preparation for the next sequence." Ukrainian forces are working to recapture territories in the south and the east, Zelensky said during his nightly address on Sunday. </li><li><strong>Russia lashes out at US:</strong> Moscow accused the US of engaging in <a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-09-19-22/h_c0bd6b5623cf9094b5e6e1a088a868e3" target="_blank">"media madness,"</a> pointing to videos and photos posted by the US embassy criticizing Russia and after President Joe Biden <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/16/politics/joe-biden-brittney-griner-and-paul-whelan-families-meeting/index.html" target="_blank">personally met</a> with the families of two American detainees last week. Russian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Maria Zakharova said "relatives were unable to get a clear explanation" from Biden about Russia's demands for a prisoner exchange, but said Russia was ready to negotiate. </li><li><strong>Russian pop legend speaks out against war: </strong>Musical legend Alla Pugacheva <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/19/europe/russia-pugacheva-galkin-ukraine-intl/index.html" target="_blank">criticized the country</a> as havingillusory aims in Ukraineon Sunday. She posted her comments on Instagram while expressing support for her husband, Maxim Galkin, a comedian who was designated a foreign agent by Russias Justice Ministry on Friday under a draconian law to rid the country of foreign influence and funding.</li><li><strong>Moscow rebuffs accusations of war crimes:</strong> Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov dismissed <a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-09-19-22/h_3a1d2f2aca7f5de72553557a1a15648e" target="_blank">Zelenskys statement</a> about Russian war crimes in recaptured territories in northeast Ukraine as a lie." The Ukrainian Defense Ministry said least <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/16/europe/ukraine-izium-mass-burial-site-intl-hnk/index.html" target="_blank">440 "unmarked" graves were found</a> in newly liberated Izium in recent days, following Russia's hasty retreat from the city. Zelensky said that some of the bodies showed "signs of torture," and blamed Russia for what he called "cruelty and terrorism."</li></ul></div></div><div data-open="false" class="sc-bdVaJa sc-iyvyFf madness&quot; after Biden meets with families of jailed Americans</h2><p class="sc-gzOgki ixpUvU">From CNN's Anna Chernova</p></header><div class="sc-bdVaJa post-content-rendered render-stellar-contentstyles__Content-sc-9v7nwy-0 erzhuK"><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"></p><div class="Box-sc-1fet97o-0 image-with-captionstyles__ImageWithCaptionWrapper-sc-17jmou0-0 eWDxVG"><figure><img src="https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/digital-images/org/5697bba4-c191-448c-9f2a-fa97eb02bd90.jpg" alt="President Joe Biden met with CherelleGriner, wife ofBrittneyGriner, at the White House on September 16." class="Image-p11edh-0 gubAgz"/><figcaption>President Joe Biden met with CherelleGriner, wife ofBrittneyGriner, at the White House on September 16. (White House)</figcaption></figure></div><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"></p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Moscow says it is ready to negotiate the fate of American prisoners in Russia, but has accused the US of engaging in "media madness" after President Joe Biden personally met with the families of two American detainees last week.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Biden <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/16/politics/joe-biden-brittney-griner-and-paul-whelan-families-meeting/index.html" target="_blank">held separate meetings with the relatives</a> of professional basketballer Brittney Griner and ex-marine Paul Whelan at the White House on Friday, marking the first time he personally convened them since the two were detained.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Instead of fulfilling its direct official duties -- maintaining contacts with the diplomats of the host country -- the US Embassy in Moscow is engaged in some kind of media madness, Russian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Maria Zakharova said in a statement on Telegram on Monday, pointing to videos and "funny pictures" posted by the US embassy in Moscow, as well as Biden's meeting. </p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">"Relatives were unable to get a clear explanation from the President of the United States about Russia's demands for a prisoner exchange," she said, adding that she learned of the details of the meeting through a CNN report citing Cherelle Griner, Brittney's wife.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">She added that she would have to turn to Whelan and Griner's relatives herself. </p><div class="sc-bdVaJa sc-RefOD bkVmOx"><blockquote class="sc-dnqmqq hJIoKL">We have stated many times that we are ready for negotiations to resolve the fate of convicted US citizens in Russia and Russian citizens convicted in the United States."</blockquote></div><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">If the US Embassy in Moscow has a minute of free time they will tell President Biden about it, and he, in turn, will tell the relatives of Whelan and Griner, Zakharova said.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Following Griner's sentencing in August, the US and Russia indicated they were <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/05/europe/griner-russia-prisoner-swap-lavrov-intl-hnk/index.html" target="_blank">ready to hold talks</a> over a prisoner swap. </p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Griner was detained in February, accused of carrying vape cartridges containing cannabis oil in her luggage. The two-time US Olympic basketball gold medalist pleaded guilty to drug charges and said she accidentally packed the drugs while in a hurry. She has been sentenced to nine years, along with a fine of around $16,400. Her legal team in Russia has appealed the sentence.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Whelan has been imprisoned in Russia for more than three years after being convicted on espionage charges that he denies. He was sentenced in June 2020 to 16 years in prison in a trial US officials denounced as unfair.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">In the meetings, Biden reiterated "his continued commitment to working through all available avenues to bring Brittney and Paul home safely," White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre said in a statement on Friday. The President appreciated the opportunity to learn more about Brittney and Paul from those who love them most, and acknowledged that every minute they are being held is a minute too long."</p></div><div data-open="false" class="sc-bdVaJa sc-iyvyFf hoANdN"><div class="sc-gzVnrw htmtru"><button aria-label="Open social share" data-open="false" class="sc-kPVwWT eUMOKF"><svg render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">In her post, Pugacheva said her husband wished for an end to the death of Russian soldiers, who were dying for illusory aims that make our erzhuK"><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">A group of human rights defenders has issued an appeal to the Russian prosecutor general to investigate reports of prisoners being sent to war in Ukraine.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Information was widely disseminated (in the show Besogon TV,' [and] in the show Vesti on the Russia-1 channel " on Sunday, August 7, 2022) that now throughout Russia there are thousands of prisoners with unserved terms for [committing] various -- including serious crimes --who are sent to Ukraine to participate in a special military operation, the activists stated in the letter addressed to Russian Prosecutor General Igor Krasnov.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">"In connection with the above, we ask you to clarify, on what basis are these persons released from prison, if this information is true? the appeal asked.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The appeal also stated that prisoners should only be released before finishing their sentence under certain terms: a pardon from the President, amnesty from the State Duma, or parole by a court decision.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The activists that signed the appeal are associated with the Human Rights Council of St. Petersburg, a Russian NGO which monitors human rights violations.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB"><strong>Some context: </strong>CNN has done prior investigative reporting on the increasing evidence that prisoners across Russia have been But this is not a lull. This is preparation for the next sequence," Zelensky said. </blockquote></div><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">"For the next sequence of words that are very important to us all and that definitely must be heard.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">The words that must be heard are the names of liberated cities, according to Zelensky.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Izium, Balakliya, Kupyansk and the Kharkiv region in general are the cities and communities that we have liberated. These words are heard now. They are heard everywhere, he said.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Mariupol, Melitopol and Kherson are also heard, but they will sound even more often and louder when we liberate them, he continued.</p><p class="sc-gZMcBi render-stellar-contentstyles__Paragraph-sc-9v7nwy-2 dCwndB">Donetsk, Horlivka and Luhansk -- they will be heard as well. Dzhankoy, Yevpatoriya, Yalta -- and they will, too.             "articleBody": "Until a few weeks ago, it looked as thoughthe conflict in Ukrainewould head into the bitter winter months frozen in place -- with neither side making appreciable progress. That prognosis has changed with the sudden and successful Ukrainian offensive through most of occupied Kharkiv, which has galvanized Ukraine's Western backers as much as it has led to recriminations in Moscow. The Russian military must now ask itself what sort of force, and where exactly they are deployed, can regain the initiative after Ukraine captured more territory in one week than Russian forces had in five months. Ukraine's stunning counteroffensive across Kharkiv, combined with more attritional advances in the south, has presented the Kremlin and Russia's much-criticized Defense Ministry with a range of bad options. As winter approaches, they must choose which front to prioritize, and whether to double down on efforts to fulfill Putin's stated objective: the seizure of Donetsk and Luhansk regions. The Russians currently hold about 20% of Ukrainian land, including Crimea and parts of the south. There are important political dynamics involved too. The Kremlin faces tough choices: whether to declare a general mobilization to reinvigorate its increasingly ragged units in Ukraine and how to manage a budget deficit -- even though it'ssitting on historically high foreign reserves. Far beyond the theater of war,Russiamust choose how far to weaponize its influence over Europe's gas supply, as governments prepare to spend big to mitigate the effects of exceptionally tight supply. body{overflow:visible;}</style></head><body><div id="mount"><div class="Chrome__component"><span style="font-size:0"></span><div class=""><div class="StickyTop__ad" style="transition:max-height 0.6s cubic-bezier(0.23, 1, 0.32, 1);max-height:none"><div class="Ad__component"><div id="ad_bnr_atf_01" class="Ad__tag"></div></div></div><span style="font-size:0"></span><div class="Header__container Header__isShown"><div class="Header__component header" style="transition:transform 0.6s cubic-bezier(0.23, 1, 0.32, 1);transform:translateY(0)"><div class="Header__wrapper"><div class="Header__logo"><a class="Header__logoCNN" href="/" target="_self"></a><a class="Header__logoTravel" href="/travel" target="_self"></a></div><div class="Header__navigation"><a class="Header__section" href="/travel/destinations" target="_self">Destinations</a><a class="Header__section" href="/travel/food-and-drink" target="_self">Food &amp; Drink</a><a class="Header__section" href="/travel/news" target="_self">News</a><a class="Header__section" href="/travel/stay" target="_self">Stay</a><a class="Header__section Header__video" href="/travel/videos" target="_self">Video</a><div class="Header__search"><span class="Header__hidden">Search</span></div><div class="Header__burger"><div class="Header__burgerIcon"><span class="Header__hidden">Menu</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div style="transition:padding-top 0.6s cubic-bezier(0.23, 1, 0.32, 1);padding-top:50px"></div><div class="Chrome__content"><div></div><div></div><div class="sc-fONwsr kqJjsk"><div class="Article__component Article__hasEntitlement"><div class="Zone__component Article__zone"><div class="Article__pageTop"><div class="Article__wrapper Article__topWrapper"><div class="Article__pageHead Article__pad"><h1 class="Article__title">Paris subway station renamed &#x27;Elizabeth II&#x27; for day of Queen&#x27;s funeral</h1><div class="Article__subtitle">Ben Morse and Xiaofei Xu, CNN<!-- -->  <!-- -->Published 19th September 2022</div></div><div class="Article__head Article__pad"><div class="SocialBar__component SocialBar__horizontal Article__socialBar"><span class="SocialBar__icon SocialBar__facebook">Facebook</span><span class="SocialBar__icon SocialBar__twitter">Twitter</span><span class="SocialBar__icon SocialBar__email">Email</span></div><div class="Article__entitlement"><div data-ad-branding="default" id="ad_mod_85a882a72"></div></div></div></div><div class="Hero__component"><div class="Hero__wrapper"><div class="Hero__imageWrapper"><div class="Image__component Image__hasAspectRatio" style="padding-top:56.25%"><img class="Image__image" src="https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/e_blur:500,q_auto:low,w_50,c_fill,g_auto,h_28,ar_16:9/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F220919083925-01-paris-metro-station-renamed-elizabeth-ii-sign.jpg" alt="TOPSHOT - A sign in the Parisian underground metro station &quot;George V&quot; is temporarily replaced with a placard reading &quot;Elizabeth II 1926-2022&quot;, in the Parisian Metro station George V, in Paris, on September 19, 2022. - Parisian metro operator RATP is temporarily renaming its &quot;George V&quot; metro station to &quot;Elizabeth II&quot; for one day, to coincide with the state funeral of the late queen, on September 19, 2022. (Photo by Thomas SAMSON / AFP) (Photo by THOMAS SAMSON/AFP via Getty Images)"/></div></div></div></div></div><div class="Article__wrapper"><div class="Article__primary"><div><div class="Article__content"><div class="Article__pad"><div class="Article__body Article__hasReadMore" style="max-height:"><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_CCB15902-9E53-34D3-987A-55B6D659D1BA"><cite class="Paragraph__cite">(CNN)  </cite><span>The <a href="https://cnn.com/travel/destinations/paris" target="_blank">Paris</a> transportation network RATP announced it has changed the name of one of its stations to honor <a href="https://cnn.com/uk/live-news/funeral-queen-elizabeth-intl-gbr/index.html" target="_blank">Queen Elizabeth II</a> on the day of her funeral. </span></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_EE9B372B-00DC-23BC-0678-55BA9D63841E"><span>The George V Mtro station, on Line 1 under the Champs-lyses, was renamed after the late Queen for the day.</span></div><div><div class="Ad__component"><div id="ad_rect_atf_02" class="Ad__tag Article__adBody Ad__hasLabel"></div></div></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_91CBB284-6266-36B0-9CC4-55BA9E6B0561"><span>"The RATP group is paying tribute to the Queen of England by renaming the George V station to Elizabeth II for the day," it said in a <a href="https://twitter.com/RATPgroup/status/1571734208984260609?s=20&t=opzc4PqK1E_06_dotD_lnw" target="_blank">statement</a> on Twitter Monday, accompanied by a picture of a plaque in the station with the Queen's name and the years of her birth and death.  </span></div><div class="CaptionedImage__component"><div class="Image__component CaptionedImage__image Image__hasAspectRatio" style="padding-top:56.25%"><img class="Image__image" src="https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/e_blur:500,q_auto:low,w_50,c_fill,g_auto,h_28,ar_16:9/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F220919083930-02-paris-metro-station-renamed-elizabeth-ii-queen.jpg" alt="Queen Elizabeth II visits Paris Flower Market on June 7, 2014."/></div><div class="CaptionedImage__caption">Queen Elizabeth II visits Paris Flower Market on June 7, 2014.</div><div class="CaptionedImage__credit">Chris Jackson/Getty Images</div></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_AA33D375-C87D-DE71-C817-55DEEE06CDD5"><span>The station was named George V after the late Queen's grandfather, King George V.</span></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_7D2120BC-C4B4-EE69-8014-55BAA10F449E"><span>RATP added in reply to a question from a customer: "The change is temporary and we are only changing one out of two plates so as not to create trouble or problems for our travelers."</span></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_C075D3BB-7CF9-69DD-76E4-55C15E2AC46F"><span>The tribute comes on the day of the Queen's funeral, which French President Emmanuel Macron attended. </span></div><div class="Ad__component"><div id="ad_nat_btf_01" class="Ad__tag"></div></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_3A914716-DFB2-797C-A002-55C4331EE348"><span>In the hours after the Queen's death, the French presidential palace <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/uk/live-news/queen-elizabeth-health-concerns-intl-gbr/h_eccbed61584836c2e308be896466f644" target="_blank">paid tribute</a> to her, thanking her for the role she played in modern history and the Franco-British relationship. </span></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_92E085E1-D672-95F7-D573-55C62C1F2FB2"><span>"She held a special status in France and a special place in the hearts of the French people," the lyse Palace said in a statement.</span></div><div class="Article__adVideo" style="display:none"><div class="Article__outStreamVideo"><button class="Article__closeBtn"></button></div><div><div class="Ad__component"><div id="ad_out_vid_01" class="Ad__tag"></div></div></div></div><div class="RelatedArticle__component"><div class="RelatedArticle__label">Related content</div><a class="RelatedArticle__link" href="/2022/09/19/uk/queen-piper-funeral-westminster-gbr-intl-scli/index.html" target="_blank">The piper who woke the Queen up every morning is playing her to rest</a></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_0DF7D4FA-6B92-760E-2BDA-55C6DF4D297A"><span>The Queen "loved France, which loved her back," it added.</span></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_DBB805A9-7AAD-9001-CFD7-55C62C21A596"><span>Queen Elizabeth II held the record for most visits to the lyse Palace for a foreign sovereign. At various occasions, including the six state visits she made to France, the Queen has met with all eight presidents of the French Fifth Republic, which was established in 1959, according to the statement. </span></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_FA10F907-217E-C730-DF5A-55C62C22388A"><span>The Queen was fluent in French and made several public speeches in French while visiting the country.</span></div><div class="Paragraph__component" data-paragraph-id="paragraph_1AFE3FFC-1BE3-B2F0-6ECE-55C62C223D3E"><span>"She who stood with the giants of the twentieth century on the path of history has now left to join them," the statement said.</span></div><div class="Paragraph__component Article__footer"><span><em>To get updates on the British Royal Family sent to your inbox, </em><a href="https://cnn.com/specials/royal-news" target="_blank"><em>sign up for CNN's Royal News newsletter</em></a>.</span></div></div></div><div class="Article__contentTail"><div class="Zone__component Article__zone Article__contentTailZone"><div style="height:100%" class="lazyload-placeholder"></div></div><div class="Zone__component Article__zone Article__promo"><div class="PromoBestBeaches__component"><a class="" href="//www.cnn.com/interactive/travel/best-beaches" target="_self"><div class="PromoBestBeaches__content"><span class="PromoBestBeaches__titleTop">A year of the world&#x27;s</span><span class="PromoBestBeaches__beaches">Best Beaches</span><span class="PromoBestBeaches__titleBottom">There&#x27;s a perfect beach for every week of the year.
